When I first started acting, all I wanted was to be taken seriously. Then I was on cast on Veronica’s Closet and Kirstie Alley told me I was funny every single day, and I believed her. She changed my life. That show changed my career. She threw legendary parties, had a wicked sense of humor and believed in me at the most tender time of my career. She told me I should have my own TV show, daily. When she heard I was testing for a pilot, she called the director at home to tell him to cast me. I made her laugh, and that meant something. I’ll never forget when we wrapped Veronica’s Closet and she gave out parakeets to the entire cast and crew. Seriously—like 400 parakeets, because she thought it was funny. Watch an episode of Cheers tonight and I promise she will make you laugh. #kirstiealley ❤️

A couple of days ago, I saw an ad, I Tweeted about it, and then this happened. At first I was panicked—actors usually want their name in @deadline announcing a job, not talking about how we get them. But within minutes of the article dropping, my phone blew up with texts from actor friends and casting directors, thanking me for speaking out. Praising @realmerrindungey and @realspragueg for having the courage to say what so many of them have been feeling. My panic quickly turned to pride. Being an actor in a self-tape world is hard. It’s expensive (please don’t tell me to get a good light and a great reader—it’s more complicated than that) it’s lonely, and discouraging. Now I’m not sure speaking up will change anything, but I’m so happy that the conversation is finally happening. My fellow actors, I love you and miss sitting in waiting rooms with you. My incredible Casting Directors, I miss being in a room with you, feeling your energy rooting for me to get the job. I miss your direction (they are called casting directors for a reason), your notes, your support. There are now three articles about this on Deadline, and I urge you to read them. Special shout out to @bonnieezane @jennifer_euston_casting @lizdeancasting and to my agent @prosicker and everyone at Gersh for supporting me and my big mouth.

Hi, I’m running to be on the @sagaftra LA Local Board and a convention delegate and I would love if you would vote for me and my fellow #unity2023 candidates. 
As you may or may not know, I put my toe in union political waters last election cycle, and found myself caught in the crossfires of infighting between @membershipfirst and @uniteforstrength so I vowed never to run again unless the two united. Well, they have. Unite for Strength and Membership First have made the bold move to run as one ticket. One ticket united for one union.
I’m throwing my full support behind @officialfrandrescher for National President and @msjoelyfisher as National Secretary-Treasurer of the UNITY slate. 
The stakes have never been higher and I would be honored to serve my union and my fellow union members.  I am # 36 for LA Local and # 198 for Convention Delegate. Please vote for unity. 

#membershipfirst 
#uniteforstrength 
#unityslate 
#unity2023 
#sagaftra

I spent the morning with my @sagaftra family and my @wgawest extended family at a rally on Melrose outside of a studio I used to call home. To my fellow out of work actors and writers and crew (and, and, and…), if you are feeling low, come to the picket line. If you miss your old friends, come to the picket line. If you’re hungry, come to the picket line. If you want to feel lifted up and supported by your beautiful peers, COME TO THE PICKET LINE. I’m a 3rd generation actor, and I’ve never been more proud to be a union member. This strike as been long and hard, but the overwhelming solidarity and support coming from people I respect has eased my pain and lifted my spirits. Thank you to everyone who showed up today—I love you all! I will see the rest of you on the picket line soon. #sagaftrastrong #wgastrong #sagaftra #strike #insolidarity #union

My first paid union job was in The Right Stuff playing Gordo Cooper’s daughter. @dennisquaid and I would drive out to Edward’s Air Force Base before the sun came up and I’d spend my day in pigtails playing in the dust. Before this, I had just started getting an allowance, and my grandmother told me that she would match any money I earned. You know where this is going, right? The @sagaftra day rates I received on that film were matched by my grandmother and put in the bank. When turned 18, I used the money to buy my first computer to bring to college. #sagaftrastrong #onstrike @sagaftra.stories #therightstuff

Like many of you, I have spent the last few days overwhelmed by the absolute horrors that have unfolded in Israel. I have seen images that I cannot unsee, heard cries for help that  I cannot unhear, and read stories that I will never forget. Heartbroken is an understatement. 
This morning, I decided to get out of the house and walk with my union family as our negotiation committee works to secure the future of our industry. In this time of unemployment and isolation, the picket line makes me feel less alone, and honestly, I  needed that today. I needed a shared human experience with my peers to lift me up, so that i can in turn lift someone else up down the road. My union put me back on my feet today.
I stand with Israel and pray this bloodshed ends. I pray for the hostages and children and grandparents and soldiers and those with loved ones bearing unspeakable grief. I wish there was something I could do, but for now the only thing I know how to do is to try to keep standing on my two feet so that I can lift someone else up when hey need it.

One day longer. One day stronger. 

@sagaftra #sagaftrastrong #sagaftra

One day longer. One day stronger.

My first real memory of being on a film set was The Big Red One. It was filmed on location in Israel, and I vividly remember the ocean. It felt bigger than any ocean I had ever seen, and I grew up in California! I  remember the heat.  I remember trying to stay cool on the beach with ice cold water bags — they kept coolers at video village, and you’d bite the corner off the bag and let the cool water drip over your head. 
As I sit here in Los Angeles, (with my union on strike, but picketing suspended today for safety concerns) watching war unfold in real time, I’ve been flooded with these memories of being a child in Israel. Reading of the murder and terror Hamas has inflicted on the people of Israel has cracked my heart in two. It’s all too much to bear. 
To my Jewish friends who I know are suffering unimaginable grief and pain, I am sending you all the love in my heart. I pray for Israel and I pray for peace. 
Stay safe out there today, everyone. ❤️

I want the strike to end. I want to go back to work more than anything, but we can’t do that until we have a deal. And we can’t make a deal if the AMPTP won’t come back to the table and negotiate with @sagaftra . One day longer. One day stronger.

This is my husband @cobybrownmusic during cancer treatment in 2006. My @sagaftra healthcare covers our family and is the reason he got the best medical care there is. As we enter day 100 of the strike, I’d like to remind everyone what this is really about. It’s not about movie stars, it’s about working class actors making a living wage for doing their job. The giant studios make billions of dollars off of our labor, and all we are asking for is a very small piece of their ample earnings. Please don’t get distracted by Halloween costume restrictions or A list zoom meetings—that’s low hanging fruit. Crews are out of work and actors are at risk of losing their healthcare every day this strike goes on. I’m tired and I’m frightened, but I’m not giving up. If you follow me and are a union member, I urge you to show your support on the picket line or on social media. We need you. One day longer. One day stronger. #sagaftrastrong #sagaftra #sagaftrastrike #fuckcancer #healthcare

You guys, I had an in person audition today for the first time since February 5, 2020. I changed my clothes 20 times, got lost on the lot and parked in someone else’s reserved spot, but it was literally a perfect day. Being in a room with the writer and producers, and reading with the casting directors that know my work— it was truly wonderful. Of course I hope I got it, but no matter the outcome, it was a day well spent. If you’re in the business and have the option of seeing actors in person again, I highly reccommend it. 10/10 #actorslife
